<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="94" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,696,1446,1473]" box="[151,696,1446,1473]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,696,1446,1473]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,696,1446,1473]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">
4.3 
<taxonomicName authority="Salvadori, 1878" authorityName="Salvadori" authorityYear="1878" box="[195,696,1446,1473]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aeruginosus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[195,494,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">Cacomantis aeruginosus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Salvadori, T." box="[502,696,1446,1472]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" pagination="456 - 463" refId="ref27221" refString="Salvadori, T. (1878) Prodromus Ornithologiae Papuasiae et Moluccarum. Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova, 13, 456 - 463." type="journal article" year="1878">Salvadori, 1878</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1519,2014]" box="[151,1406,1519,1545]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,236,1519,1545]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">Range:</emphasis>
North and south 
<collectingCountry box="[431,543,1519,1545]" name="Indonesia" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">Moluccas</collectingCountry>
, perhaps limited to the main islands of Buru, 
<collectingCountry box="[1051,1135,1519,1545]" name="Indonesia" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">Ambon</collectingCountry>
and Seram in the south.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="95" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1519,2014]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,1554,1581]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
main song of 
<specimenCount box="[489,602,1555,1581]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" type="generic" typeStatus="types">two types</specimenCount>
, one representing the main song in the rest of the complex with elements resembling those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="S. Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[383,506,1591,1617]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sepulcralis">
<emphasis box="[383,506,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">sepulcralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but more variable in form (
<figureCitation box="[824,894,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1697,1721]" captionTargetBox="[388,1205,925,1672]" captionTargetId="figure-251@11.[378,1210,921,1673]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 2. The seven element shapes found in the Cacomantis variolosus complex. Taxon names given represent the following geographic song types (see Results): sepulcralis—Sundaland and Philippines, virescens—Sulawesi and Sula, aeruginosus—resident Moluccas, variolosus—Australasia, blandus—Admiralty Islands, addendus—Solomon Islands." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5840531" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5840531/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), and the other a unique and more frequent ‘locomotive’ vocalization of prolonged series of rapidly uttered clipped whistles on the same pitch; basic morph of Wallacean morphotype (see 3.2.2(2) above), but paler with light copper-green dorsal sheen and mid brownish rufous ventral surface, and extensive white toothing on inner vanes of outer rectrices; body medium-sized and tail proportionally long: wing 
<emphasis box="[410,422,1735,1760]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">c</emphasis>
. 
<quantity box="[437,587,1735,1761]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.17" metricValueMax="1.22" metricValueMin="1.1199999999999999" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" unit="mm" value="117.0" valueMax="122.0" valueMin="112.0">112–122 mm</quantity>
, tail/wing ratio 1.02–1.14 (
<tableCitation box="[892,979,1735,1761]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,244,466,493]" captionTargetBox="[165,2020,579,1643]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 2. Measurements and proportions of regional forms and populations of the Cacomantis variolosus complex. Bracketed measurements are of extreme ranges; those in between cover 75% of variation. Records of numbers of morphs per population are not exhaustive because morphs were not recorded for all museum collections. Abbreviations: M—males, F—females." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF346630FFBEFFA086B269F4FDDDFD91" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" tableUuid="DF346630FFBEFFA086B269F4FDDDFD91">Table 2</tableCitation>
); barred females with dorsa dully barred dusky on cinnamon, and ventral white barred clearly black with moderate, if variable, cinnamon wash; juveniles dark-toned with fine markings.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1519,2014]" lastBlockId="26.[151,1436,151,357]" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="95" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">
The ‘locomotive’ vocalization (
<bibRefCitation author="Rheindt, F. E. &amp; Hutchinson, R. O." box="[549,869,1843,1869]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" pagination="18 - 38" refId="ref26927" refString="Rheindt, F. E. &amp; Hutchinson, R. O. (2007) A photoshot odyssey through the confused avian taxonomy of Seram and Buru (southern Moluccas). BirdingASIA, 7, 18 - 38." type="journal article" year="2007">Rheindt &amp; Hutchinson 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Tebb, G. &amp; Morris, P. &amp; Los, P." box="[880,1064,1843,1869]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" pagination="67 - 76" refId="ref27806" refString="Tebb, G., Morris, P. &amp; Los, P. (2008) New and interesting bird records from Sulawesi and Halmahera, Indonesia. BirdingASIA, 10, 67 - 76." type="journal article" year="2008">
Tebb 
<emphasis box="[942,998,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Thibault, M. &amp; du Rau, P. D. &amp; Pineau, O. &amp; Pangimangen, W." box="[1074,1296,1843,1869]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" pagination="83 - 115" refId="ref27843" refString="Thibault, M., du Rau, P. D., Pineau, O. &amp; Pangimangen, W. (2013) New and interesting records for the Obi Archipelago (north Maluku, Indonesia), including field observations and first description of the vocalisation of Moluccan Woodcock Scolopax rochussenii. Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club, 133 (2), 83 - 115." type="journal article" year="2013">
Thibault 
<emphasis box="[1176,1225,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">et al</emphasis>
. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
) has provided grounds for separating this form from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="S. Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[608,731,1879,1905]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sepulcralis">
<emphasis box="[608,731,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">sepulcralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at species rank (del Hoyo &amp; Collar 2014; 
<bibRefCitation author="Clements, J. F. &amp; Schulenberg, T. S. &amp; Iliff, M. J. &amp; Billerman, S. M. &amp; Fredericks, T. A. &amp; Sullivan, B. L. &amp; Wood, C. L." box="[1199,1431,1879,1905]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" refId="ref23387" refString="Clements, J. F., Schulenberg, T. S., Iliff, M. J., Billerman, S. M., Fredericks, T. A., Sullivan, B. L. &amp; Wood, C. L. (2019) The eBird / Clements Checklist of Birds of the World: v 2019. Available from: https: // www. birds. cornell. edu / clementschecklist / download / (accessed 19 September 2020)" type="url" year="2019">
Clements 
<emphasis box="[1311,1367,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gill, F. &amp; Donsker, D. &amp; Rasmussen, P." box="[151,324,1915,1941]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" refId="ref24352" refString="Gill, F., Donsker, D. &amp; Rasmussen, P. (2021) IOC World Bird List. Version 11.2. Available from: http: // www. worldbirdnames. org / new / ioc-lists / master-list- 2 / (accessed 19 September 2020) https: // doi. org / 10.14344 / IOC. ML. 11.1" type="url" year="2021">
Gill 
<emphasis box="[202,258,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">et al.</emphasis>
2021
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Payne, R. B." box="[343,493,1914,1941]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" refId="ref26605" refString="Payne, R. B. (2005) The Cuckoos. Oxford University Press, London, xxii + 618 pp." type="book" year="2005">Payne (2005)</bibRefCitation>
assessed its populations as intergradient with dorsiventrally greyer Australo-Papuan 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vigors &amp; Horsfield" authorityYear="1827" box="[151,268,1951,1977]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="variolosus">
<emphasis box="[151,268,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">variolosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, using comments from 
<bibRefCitation author="Hartert, E." box="[528,688,1950,1977]" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" pagination="164 - 174" refId="ref24871" refString="Hartert, E. (1925) Review of the genus Cacomantis Mull. Novitates Zoologicae, 32, 164 - 174. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 4504" type="journal article" year="1925">Hartert (1925)</bibRefCitation>
in support. We read those comments as referring instead to putative intergradation between two subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vigors &amp; Horsfield" authorityYear="1827" box="[618,735,1987,2013]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="94" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="variolosus">
<emphasis box="[618,735,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">variolosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the 
<collectingCountry box="[811,920,1987,2013]" name="Indonesia" pageId="25" pageNumber="94">Moluccas</collectingCountry>
(see 4.4.1.1 below). Adding to the original six AMNH specimens of the north Moluccan population (
<taxonomicName authority="Stresemann, 1931" authorityName="Stresemann" authorityYear="1931" box="[769,1083,151,177]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="heinrichi">
<emphasis box="[769,870,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="95">heinrichi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Stresemann, E." box="[878,1083,151,177]" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" pagination="167 - 171" refId="ref27725" refString="Stresemann, E. (1931) Vorlaufiges uber die ornithologischen Ergebnisse der Expedition Heinrich 1930 - 1931. V. Zur Ornithologie von Halmahera und Batjan. Ornithologische Monatsberichte, 39, 167 - 171." type="journal article" year="1931">Stresemann, 1931</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
), we have now traced a further six in AMNH, RMNH, ANSP, identified by tail/wing ratios greater than 1.02. The resulting series, from Obi, Bacan and Halmahera, is uniform in plumage and long-tailed (
<tableCitation box="[767,852,223,249]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,244,466,493]" captionTargetBox="[165,2020,579,1643]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 2. Measurements and proportions of regional forms and populations of the Cacomantis variolosus complex. Bracketed measurements are of extreme ranges; those in between cover 75% of variation. Records of numbers of morphs per population are not exhaustive because morphs were not recorded for all museum collections. Abbreviations: M—males, F—females." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF346630FFBEFFA086B269F4FDDDFD91" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" tableUuid="DF346630FFBEFFA086B269F4FDDDFD91">Table 2</tableCitation>
), without any phenotypic sign of intergradation with Moluccan populations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vigors &amp; Horsfield" authorityYear="1827" box="[442,559,259,285]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="variolosus">
<emphasis box="[442,559,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="95">variolosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. If the main song common to the complex is ancestral, then the ‘locomotive’ vocalization in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salvadori" authorityYear="1878" box="[324,461,295,320]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aeruginosus">
<emphasis box="[324,461,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="95">aeruginosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may well have developed as an isolating mechanism against migrant and, in the north, resident populations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vigors &amp; Horsfield" authorityYear="1827" box="[415,532,331,357]" class="Aves" family="Cuculidae" genus="Cacomantis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cuculiformes" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="variolosus">
<emphasis box="[415,532,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="95">variolosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
